        <h3>Flights to New York</h3>
        <p>New York City, often simply referred to as New York, is one of the most iconic and vibrant cities in the world. Known for its diversity, cultural significance, and bustling energy, New York is a global hub for finance, art, entertainment, and fashion. It's also famous for its skyline, historical landmarks, and a wide range of attractions that draw millions of tourists each year.</p>

        <h4>Key Information:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Overview:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Location:</strong> New York City is located in the state of New York, on the northeastern coast of the United States. It consists of five boroughs: Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island.</li>
                    <li><strong>Population:</strong> With a population of over 8 million people, New York City is the most populous city in the United States and one of the most culturally diverse cities in the world.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Famous Landmarks:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Statue of Liberty:</strong> A symbol of freedom and democracy, the Statue of Liberty stands on Liberty Island in New York Harbor.</li>
                    <li><strong>Empire State Building:</strong> Once the tallest building in the world, it offers breathtaking views of the city.</li>
                    <li><strong>Times Square:</strong> Known for its neon lights and entertainment hubs, Times Square is a must-visit.</li>
                    <li><strong>Central Park:</strong> A massive park in Manhattan, perfect for walking and relaxation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Broadway:</strong> The theater capital of the world, offering a range of spectacular shows.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Cultural Diversity:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Ethnic Neighborhoods:</strong> Diverse neighborhoods like Chinatown, Little Italy, and Harlem reflect the city's rich cultural fabric.</li>
